Overview
Milkdown is a lightweight but powerful WYSIWYG markdown editor. It's made up by two parts: A tiny core which provide markdown parser, serializer and kinds of plugin loader. Lots of plugins provide syntax, commands and components. With this pattern you can enable or disable any custom syntax you like, such as table, latex and slash commands. online editor documentation github üìù WYSIWYG Markdown - Write markdown in an elegant way üé® Themable - Theme can be shared and used with npm packages üéÆ Hackable - Support your awesome idea by plugin ü¶æ Reliable - Built on top of prosemirror and remark
‚ö°Ô∏è Slash & Tooltip - Write fast for everyone, driven by plugin üßÆ Math - LaTeX math equations support, driven by plugin üìä Table - Table support with fluent ui, driven by plugin Milkdown is built on top of these tools: Prosemirror and it's community - A toolkit for building rich-text editors on the web Remark and it's community - Markdown parser done right Postcss - Powerful css tool to build theme TypeScript - Developed by typescript Prism - Code snippets support Katex - LaTex math rendering We have some pieces for you to create a very minimal editor: We use material icon and Roboto Font in our theme. import { Editor } from '@milkdown/core'; import { commonmark } from '@milkdown/preset-commonmark';
// import theme import '@milkdown/theme-nord/lib/theme.css';
const root = document.body; new Editor({ root }).use(commonmark).create();
For further information, please visit our website.

Let's take a look on a minimal webpack configuration needed to build typescript.
index.html loads the js from the default webpack output location
<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" />
    <title>Webpack ts example</title>
    <link rel="shortcut icon" href="#" />
  </head>
  <body>
    <script type="text/javascript" src="dist/main.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>

The demo code is in src/index.ts - a file that is loaded for the default entry point. The code is simple:
const element = document.createElement("div");

element.innerHTML = "hello world!";

document.body.append(element);

For this to work, we need 2 configuration files. 
Webpack configuration goes to webpack.config.js:
module.exports = {
  resolve: {
    extensions: [".ts", ".js"],
  },
  module: {
    rules: [
      {
        test: /\.ts$/i,
        use: ["ts-loader"],
      },
    ],
  },
};

extensions: [".ts", ".js"] make webpack attempt to load ts when extension is missing, and makes it try TS before JS. Object added to module.rules[] sets ts-loader for all files that ends .ts.
The ts configuration is in tsconfig.json:
{
  "include": ["src/**/*"]
}

All dependencies that we need to install:
$ npm install --save-dev webpack ts-loader typescript

This could work would without installing typescript explicitly - but it's better idea to specify the dependency ourselves & keep it simple to pin the version if ever we will want to it.
In this article we have seen to what's the minimal webpack configuration to build ts files. If you want to play with the code, you can find the repo here:
